WEBVTT

1
00:00:53.590 --> 00:00:57.561
<i>I accept this honor for our lost ones,</i>

2
00:00:57.630 --> 00:01:00.156
<i>whose deaths pave our path.</i>

3
00:01:00.790 --> 00:01:04.397
And for the 20 million
Negro men and women


4
00:01:04.470 --> 00:01:09.158
motivated by dignity
and a disdain for hopelessness.


5
00:01:12.790 --> 00:01:15.236
This isn't right.

6
00:01:15.310 --> 00:01:16.391
Corrie.

7
00:01:16.710 --> 00:01:18.041
This ain't right.

8
00:01:18.110 --> 00:01:19.316
What's that?

9
00:01:20.030 --> 00:01:22.476
This necktie. It's not right.

10
00:01:23.950 --> 00:01:26.760
Well, it's not a necktie, dear.
It's an ascot.


11
00:01:26.830 --> 00:01:30.880
Yes, but generally the same principles
should apply, shouldn't they?


12
00:01:31.750 --> 00:01:33.514
It's not right.

13
00:01:33.790 --> 00:01:35.679
It's not right, or you don't like it?

14
00:01:36.830 --> 00:01:38.912
I don't like how this looks.

15
00:01:38.990 --> 00:01:41.561
Looks distinguished and debonair
to me.


16
00:01:41.630 --> 00:01:44.076
You know what I mean.

17
00:01:44.190 --> 00:01:47.194
Like we're living high on the hog.

18
00:01:47.270 --> 00:01:51.116
Dressed like this
while folks back home are...


19
00:01:52.190 --> 00:01:54.033
It's not right.

20
00:01:55.310 --> 00:01:58.359
Wait till the brothers back home
see me like this.


21
00:01:58.430 --> 00:01:59.761
They'll have a good laugh.

22
00:01:59.870 --> 00:02:02.157
Let them laugh.

23
00:02:02.230 --> 00:02:06.280
It's not a crime to be away
for a few days, Martin.


24
00:02:09.590 --> 00:02:12.036
It's nice being away, huh?

25
00:02:12.710 --> 00:02:14.235
Yeah. It really is.

26
00:02:15.830 --> 00:02:16.831
Look here.

27
00:02:18.750 --> 00:02:22.038
I'm gonna be a pastor
somewhere small.


28
00:02:22.710 --> 00:02:24.155
College town.

29
00:02:25.830 --> 00:02:29.960
Lead a little church. 
Teach a class.

30
00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:34.878
Maybe the occasional
speaking engagement.


31
00:02:36.430 --> 00:02:39.400
And I'll pay all the bills for us,

32
00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:42.679
especially the mortgage
for our very own house.


33
00:02:45.030 --> 00:02:46.680
Perfect.

34
00:02:59.110 --> 00:03:00.714
You look handsome.

35
00:03:02.070 --> 00:03:03.913
<i>Through it all,</i>

36
00:03:03.990 --> 00:03:09.121
Martin Luther King has
spoken of his dream.


37
00:03:09.630 --> 00:03:11.394
One which we

38
00:03:11.470 --> 00:03:15.759
and many other people
around the world share.


39
00:03:17.190 --> 00:03:22.435
To this undeterred hero for justice,

40
00:03:22.510 --> 00:03:26.071
the Nobel Committee of Oslo, Norway,

41
00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:31.600
awards our 1964 Peace Prize.

42
00:03:47.110 --> 00:03:50.796
<i>I accept this honor for our lost ones,</i>

43
00:03:50.870 --> 00:03:55.034
<i>whose deaths pave our path.</i>

44
00:03:55.110 --> 00:04:00.276
<i>I accept this honor for the more than

45
00:04:00.350 --> 00:04:03.399
<i>who are motivated by dignity.</i>

46
00:04:03.470 --> 00:04:07.077
<i>Together we believe that
what the illusion</i>


47
00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:09.471
<i>of supremacy has destroyed,</i>

48
00:04:09.910 --> 00:04:14.074
<i>the truth of equality can nourish.</i>

49
00:04:14.150 --> 00:04:16.517
I promise you.
It ain't nothing to be scared of.


50
00:04:16.630 --> 00:04:18.712
It's quick.
And the pastor is right there next to you.


51
00:04:18.790 --> 00:04:21.270
Yeah, but the biggest thing
is getting your hair wet up.


52
00:04:21.350 --> 00:04:22.761
I got my hair pressed that same morning

53
00:04:22.830 --> 00:04:24.912
and it was wasted
as soon as I hit the water.


54
00:04:24.990 --> 00:04:26.913
I should have worn a swim cap
like Mama said.


55
00:04:27.950 --> 00:04:29.236
See, I asked my mama

56
00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:31.790
could she make my hair like
Coretta Scott King had hers


57
00:04:31.870 --> 00:04:33.440
at the Washington March.

58
00:04:33.510 --> 00:04:35.160
But she said that was too grown.

59
00:04:35.230 --> 00:04:36.595
Oh, I love her hair.

60
00:04:36.670 --> 00:04:39.355
I heard she don't even put rollers in it.
It's just like that.


61
00:04:39.430 --> 00:04:41.751
But I studied it. 
I know how she do it.

62
00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:43.992
See, she parts in the middle and then...

63
00:06:41.670 --> 00:06:42.671
Annie Lee Cooper!

64
00:06:47.150 --> 00:06:50.677
Get on up now. 
I ain't got all day.

65
00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:08.631
You work for Mr. Dunn
down at the rest home, ain't that right?


66
00:07:10.310 --> 00:07:11.516
Yes.

67
00:07:12.190 --> 00:07:13.840
Wonder what old Dunn'll say
when I tell him


68
00:07:13.910 --> 00:07:16.800
one of his gals is down here
stirring a fuss.


69
00:07:16.870 --> 00:07:21.239
I ain't stirring no fuss.
I'm just here trying to register to vote.


70
00:07:25.510 --> 00:07:26.796
It's all right this time.

71
00:07:26.870 --> 00:07:28.759
It's right when I say it's right.

72
00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:36.591
Recite the Constitution's preamble.
Know what a preamble is?


73
00:07:44.710 --> 00:07:48.840
"We the people of the United States,

74
00:07:49.990 --> 00:07:52.641
"in order to form a more perfect union,

75
00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:56.996
"establish justice,

76
00:07:57.710 --> 00:08:00.475
"ensure domestic tranquility,

77
00:08:01.230 --> 00:08:05.360
"provide for the common defense,
promote the general welfare..."


78
00:08:05.430 --> 00:08:08.274
How many county judges in Alabama?

79
00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:14.520
Sixty-seven.

80
00:08:18.750 --> 00:08:20.400
Name them.

81
00:08:47.910 --> 00:08:50.675
<i>Aren't we done?
Are we not done with this?</i>


82
00:08:50.790 --> 00:08:53.031
- Will this ever end?
- I don't know, Mr. President.


83
00:08:53.110 --> 00:08:55.158
A comprehensive plan
is already in place.


84
00:08:55.230 --> 00:08:57.881
The act was only passed
six months ago.


85
00:08:57.950 --> 00:09:01.921
So hammer home that
impatience only hurts the overall cause.


86
00:09:01.990 --> 00:09:05.358
We're... We're getting there.
Just... Just keep reiterating the plan.


87
00:09:05.470 --> 00:09:06.756
No, he doesn't want reiteration.

88
00:09:06.830 --> 00:09:10.437
He wants something so he can say,
"Look, I told you I had a dream


89
00:09:10.510 --> 00:09:12.877
"and it's all coming goddamn true,
whether you like it or not!"


90
00:09:12.950 --> 00:09:14.600
That's what he wants.

91
00:09:14.670 --> 00:09:16.991
What he needs to do
is get on board with what we're doing


92
00:09:17.070 --> 00:09:19.232
instead of the other way around.
For once!


93
00:09:21.110 --> 00:09:23.636
Mr. President, Dr. King.

94
00:09:23.830 --> 00:09:25.434
Mr. President.

95
00:09:25.510 --> 00:09:27.160
Dr. King.

96
00:09:28.430 --> 00:09:30.876
Well, I'll tell you.
I'm a tall son-of-a-bitch,


97
00:09:30.950 --> 00:09:34.272
but this close to the new Nobel laureate

98
00:09:34.350 --> 00:09:36.751
and with all those other trinkets
you've been collecting lately,


99
00:09:36.830 --> 00:09:38.639
I feel tits-high to a puppy dog.

100
00:09:39.150 --> 00:09:40.720
Well, thank you, Mr. President.

101
00:09:41.710 --> 00:09:42.711
Mr. White.

102
00:09:42.790 --> 00:09:44.076
- Dr. King.
- All right.


103
00:09:44.150 --> 00:09:47.597
I'll tell you, ending segregation,

104
00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:50.992
proudest moment of my life
when I signed that '64 Act.


105
00:09:51.950 --> 00:09:54.715
Proudest moment of my life, I tell you.

106
00:09:54.790 --> 00:09:56.633
Now civil rights is a priority

107
00:09:56.710 --> 00:09:58.758
- of this administration as you know.
- Thank you.


108
00:09:58.830 --> 00:10:00.036
We're gonna face the challenge,

109
00:10:00.150 --> 00:10:03.472
or this country is
storing up a heap of trouble for itself.


110
00:10:03.550 --> 00:10:07.600
Now, seeing as I can't convince you to
work with my administration


111
00:10:07.670 --> 00:10:11.152
in an official capacity
inside the White House,


112
00:10:11.390 --> 00:10:12.630
I feel damn fortunate

113
00:10:12.710 --> 00:10:14.394
to have someone
as statesmanlike as you


114
00:10:14.470 --> 00:10:15.471
leading the movement.

115
00:10:15.550 --> 00:10:17.439
And I want you to go on leading it.
No one else.


116
00:10:17.510 --> 00:10:20.559
Not one of these
militant Malcolm X types.


117
00:10:22.190 --> 00:10:25.637
So... I wanna help. Tell me how.

118
00:10:27.590 --> 00:10:29.479
Well, Mr. President,

119
00:10:29.550 --> 00:10:33.441
I'm here to speak
specifically about the denial


120
00:10:33.510 --> 00:10:36.878
of a basic American right
for the Negro citizen.


121
00:10:37.430 --> 00:10:39.239
The right to vote.

122
00:10:41.510 --> 00:10:43.512
Well... Technically...

123
00:10:43.590 --> 00:10:47.481
Technically, we already have it.
Yes, Mr. President.


124
00:10:47.550 --> 00:10:50.679
But, we both know in the South

125
00:10:50.750 --> 00:10:54.471
black voters are kept off the rolls
and out of the voting booths


126
00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:59.078
by systematic intimidation
and fear, Mr. President.


127
00:11:00.510 --> 00:11:03.354
Now, you asked how you can help.

128
00:11:04.070 --> 00:11:06.596
We want Federal legislation

129
00:11:06.670 --> 00:11:10.516
granting Negroes the right
to vote unencumbered.


130
00:11:10.590 --> 00:11:14.037
And we want Federal
protocol eliminating


131
00:11:14.110 --> 00:11:16.681
the decades-long dismissal

132
00:11:16.750 --> 00:11:20.118
and illegal denial
of blacks seeking to vote.


133
00:11:20.230 --> 00:11:24.030
And we want
robust enforcement of that protocol.


134
00:11:27.110 --> 00:11:30.034
Well... That's fine.

135
00:11:30.110 --> 00:11:34.911
But... Most of the South
is still not desegregating.


136
00:11:34.990 --> 00:11:37.596
Let's not start another battle
when we haven't even won the first.


137
00:11:39.310 --> 00:11:42.553
And you know what
the next battle should be?


138
00:11:42.670 --> 00:11:45.150
The eradication of poverty.

139
00:11:45.750 --> 00:11:47.673
I'm calling it "The War on Poverty."

140
00:11:49.430 --> 00:11:52.673
It's a matter of political priorities.

141
00:11:52.750 --> 00:11:56.800
Poverty is going to be my focus at home
and I want you to help me with this.


142
00:11:57.670 --> 00:11:59.832
We can make big changes
in these things


143
00:11:59.910 --> 00:12:01.560
for people of all colors.

144
00:12:01.630 --> 00:12:03.951
And I know that matters to you,
doesn't it?


145
00:12:04.030 --> 00:12:06.271
This voting thing
is just gonna have to wait.


146
00:12:13.030 --> 00:12:14.395
It...

147
00:12:14.470 --> 00:12:17.599
It can't wait, Mr. President.

148
00:12:17.670 --> 00:12:18.671
Well, why not?

149
00:12:18.790 --> 00:12:20.918
Because there have been thousands

150
00:12:20.990 --> 00:12:23.391
of racially motivated murders
in the South,


151
00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:25.916
including those four girls.

152
00:12:25.990 --> 00:12:27.071
Well, I know that...

153
00:12:27.150 --> 00:12:29.756
And you know the astounding fact

154
00:12:29.830 --> 00:12:34.711
that not one of these criminals
who murder us when and why they want


155
00:12:34.790 --> 00:12:36.440
has ever been convicted.

156
00:12:36.510 --> 00:12:38.194
Yeah, I know we have a lot
of work to do down there.


157
00:12:38.270 --> 00:12:39.920
Not one conviction

158
00:12:39.990 --> 00:12:43.039
because they are protected
by white officials


159
00:12:43.110 --> 00:12:45.636
chosen by an all-white electorate.

160
00:12:45.710 --> 00:12:48.554
And on the rare occasions
that they face trial,


161
00:12:48.630 --> 00:12:51.634
they are freed by all-white juries.

162
00:12:51.710 --> 00:12:56.750
All-white because
you can't serve on a jury


163
00:12:56.870 --> 00:12:59.350
unless you are registered to vote.

164
00:13:02.910 --> 00:13:07.199
Well, Dr. King, you've certainly given me
something to think about.


165
00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:10.956
But this administration is going to
set this aside for a while.


166
00:13:11.030 --> 00:13:13.397
Just for a while, you understand.

167
00:13:17.150 --> 00:13:20.677
Yes, Mr. President, I... I understand.

168
00:13:29.550 --> 00:13:31.154
Selma it is.

169
00:13:46.950 --> 00:13:48.714
Big speech lined up
for these folks tonight, Doc?


170
00:13:50.750 --> 00:13:53.356
We need to see what's what first,
Big Fellow.


171
00:13:53.590 --> 00:13:55.831
We're just here to test the waters.

172
00:13:55.910 --> 00:13:59.278
Oh, my Lord.
What you got us into, woman?


173
00:13:59.750 --> 00:14:05.678
We've got 128 miles
to come to our senses, gentlemen.


174
00:14:05.750 --> 00:14:06.990
Hush.

175
00:14:07.070 --> 00:14:09.801
This here is the
place we need to be.

176
00:14:09.870 --> 00:14:12.521
This right here is the next great battle.

177
00:14:13.230 --> 00:14:15.358
I can only imagine.

178
00:14:18.470 --> 00:14:21.679
Decent-looking place to die though.

179
00:14:46.790 --> 00:14:47.871
Ms. Nash.

180
00:14:48.270 --> 00:14:49.476
Mr. Bevel.

181
00:14:49.550 --> 00:14:53.839
Doc? This here is it. 
Selma's the place.

182
00:14:54.950 --> 00:14:58.079
A lot of groundwork has already
been laid by the people here.


183
00:14:58.150 --> 00:14:59.151
And they ready.

184
00:15:18.390 --> 00:15:20.631
- Sister Boynton.
- Mr. Orange.


185
00:15:27.830 --> 00:15:29.161
Good afternoon.

186
00:15:34.870 --> 00:15:36.838
Dr. King?

187
00:15:37.430 --> 00:15:39.831
May I introduce myself?

188
00:15:40.430 --> 00:15:42.159
Yeah, of course.

189
00:15:44.350 --> 00:15:45.397
Hey!

190
00:15:48.950 --> 00:15:50.361
It's okay. It's okay. I'm okay.

191
00:15:53.350 --> 00:15:54.476
This way, Dr. King.

192
00:15:59.670 --> 00:16:01.718
That white boy can hit.

193
00:16:01.790 --> 00:16:03.121
This place is perfect.

194
00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:06.672
What's the FBI's current information
on Martin Luther King?


195
00:16:07.230 --> 00:16:09.631
I heard he was assaulted in Selma.

196
00:16:09.710 --> 00:16:13.635
My information can be
summed up in a few words.


197
00:16:13.710 --> 00:16:17.840
King is a political and moral degenerate.

198
00:16:17.910 --> 00:16:21.631
Well, you say that, J. Edgar.
I have to take it seriously.


199
00:16:21.710 --> 00:16:24.919
But if he's a degenerate,
what I do know is,


200
00:16:24.990 --> 00:16:27.152
he's a non-violent degenerate.

201
00:16:27.230 --> 00:16:30.154
And I want him to go on leading
the civil rights movement,


202
00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:33.234
not one of these bloodthirsty militants.

203
00:16:33.310 --> 00:16:37.235
What I need to know right now is
what's he about to do next?


204
00:16:38.230 --> 00:16:39.561
Mr. President,

205
00:16:40.710 --> 00:16:45.159
you know we can
shut men with power down


206
00:16:45.230 --> 00:16:49.155
permanently and unequivocally.

207
00:16:52.670 --> 00:16:55.719
I'm very aware of that, Mr. Director.

208
00:16:59.630 --> 00:17:04.841
Well, if you prefer a different approach,

209
00:17:06.750 --> 00:17:08.434
we can go with the wife.

210
00:17:11.390 --> 00:17:15.600
We know there's tension
in the home already.


211
00:17:17.270 --> 00:17:20.797
We can weaken the dynamic.

212
00:17:23.590 --> 00:17:25.354
Dismantle the family.

213
00:17:55.790 --> 00:17:56.791
Hello.

214
00:17:56.870 --> 00:17:58.838
<i>You ain't got long.</i>

215
00:17:59.190 --> 00:18:03.479
<i>When the hearts of those Pickaninnies
of yours stop beating...</i>


216
00:18:07.430 --> 00:18:09.319
Same thing?

217
00:18:12.310 --> 00:18:13.550
When are you all heading out?

218
00:18:14.990 --> 00:18:18.836
We're heading back to Selma
at 5:00 a.m.


219
00:18:18.910 --> 00:18:22.119
It turned out to be
an ideal staging ground.


220
00:18:23.590 --> 00:18:28.198
There's a full couple of weeks planned.

221
00:18:29.590 --> 00:18:31.160
Quite a bit to be done.

222
00:18:35.350 --> 00:18:36.875
I see.

223
00:18:42.350 --> 00:18:46.560
That highway is nice now.
Get you there in a couple of hours.


224
00:18:55.390 --> 00:18:58.121
Good people in those parts though.

225
00:19:05.390 --> 00:19:06.596
Well...

226
00:19:09.270 --> 00:19:11.955
I'm worried about the ones
who ain't so good.


227
00:19:13.990 --> 00:19:18.917
This local Sheriff Jim Clark
is supposed to be bad business.


228
00:19:20.550 --> 00:19:22.552
Won't go down without a fight, they say.

229
00:19:25.030 --> 00:19:27.601
And since we don't fight...

230
00:19:28.070 --> 00:19:29.595
Well...

231
00:19:30.510 --> 00:19:33.241
As good a place to
die as any, I guess.

232
00:19:36.670 --> 00:19:38.638
I wish you wouldn't talk like that.

233
00:19:43.270 --> 00:19:45.352
It just takes the edge off.

234
00:19:47.630 --> 00:19:49.553
You and your friends
can joke about that.


235
00:19:49.630 --> 00:19:51.758
I don't joke about that.

236
00:19:55.550 --> 00:19:58.554
You're right. I'm sorry.

237
00:20:01.030 --> 00:20:04.273
I'll put these things away
in your bag now.


238
00:20:04.350 --> 00:20:07.399
I didn't realize
you were leaving so early.


239
00:20:54.310 --> 00:20:55.960
Hello?

240
00:20:56.030 --> 00:20:57.156
<i>Halie?</i>

241
00:20:57.950 --> 00:20:59.600
<i>Martin.</i>

242
00:21:01.550 --> 00:21:04.076
I need to hear the Lord's voice.

243
00:21:08.190 --> 00:21:12.036
Surely, Martin. Surely.

244
00:21:21.830 --> 00:21:28.679
<i>Precious Lord</i>

245
00:21:29.710 --> 00:21:34.193
<i>Take my hand</i>

246
00:21:35.670 --> 00:21:42.235
<i>Lead me home</i>

247
00:21:42.870 --> 00:21:47.751
<i>Let me stand</i>

248
00:21:48.230 --> 00:21:55.079
<i>I am tired</i>

249
00:21:56.790 --> 00:22:01.432
<i>I am weak</i>

250
00:22:02.590 --> 00:22:09.553
<i>I am worn</i>

251
00:22:12.670 --> 00:22:19.315
<i>Through the storm</i>

252
00:22:19.910 --> 00:22:26.919
<i>Through the night</i>

253
00:22:29.790 --> 00:22:36.674
<i>Lord, lead me on</i>

254
00:22:37.190 --> 00:22:39.511
<i>To the light</i>

255
00:22:42.230 --> 00:22:43.994
- Hey!
- Hey!


256
00:22:44.070 --> 00:22:45.560
- Sully.
- Look at you.


257
00:22:46.750 --> 00:22:49.037
- Morning, Doctor.
- Good morning, Doctor.


258
00:22:49.110 --> 00:22:51.716
- Drive all right?
- Good and long.


259
00:22:51.790 --> 00:22:54.714
Good news is Richie Jean is in there.

260
00:22:54.790 --> 00:22:57.191
Oh, she's ready for you.

261
00:22:57.830 --> 00:23:00.310
Negro, that's all you had to say.

262
00:23:01.630 --> 00:23:03.280
Uncle Marty!

263
00:23:03.390 --> 00:23:05.631
There she is! There's our girl!

264
00:23:06.430 --> 00:23:08.751
Hey, Richie Jean!

265
00:23:10.470 --> 00:23:12.279
- Looking like her mom.
- You go play.


266
00:23:12.350 --> 00:23:14.876
- Hey!
- Hey, Ralphy.


267
00:23:16.110 --> 00:23:17.600
- How you doing?
- Hey!


268
00:23:17.670 --> 00:23:18.717
Good to see you, sweetheart.

269
00:23:18.790 --> 00:23:20.280
Hey, come over here.

270
00:23:22.030 --> 00:23:23.475
Oh, Lord, it's good to see this!

271
00:23:23.550 --> 00:23:25.632
Okay, now, I've got the grits
on the stove.


272
00:23:25.710 --> 00:23:27.678
How many we expecting today?

273
00:23:27.790 --> 00:23:30.031
Well, now, Sister Jackson.

274
00:23:30.110 --> 00:23:32.716
You know about our group,
the SCLC, right?


275
00:23:32.790 --> 00:23:34.758
The Southern Christian
Leadership Conference?


276
00:23:34.830 --> 00:23:37.276
A few of our top SCLC leaders
are with us this time


277
00:23:37.350 --> 00:23:40.797
since we're going to be here
a little longer than expected.


278
00:23:41.230 --> 00:23:42.880
Now, this here's Reverend C.T. Vivian.

279
00:23:42.950 --> 00:23:44.679
He coordinates all the SCLC branches.

280
00:23:44.750 --> 00:23:47.435
Welcome. Nice to meet you.
Welcome, welcome.


281
00:23:47.510 --> 00:23:49.353
This is Reverend James Bevel.

282
00:23:49.430 --> 00:23:51.478
- How you doing, ma'am?
- I'm well. Thank you.


283
00:23:51.550 --> 00:23:53.075
This here is James Orange.

284
00:23:53.190 --> 00:23:54.601
Oh, this is a big one.

285
00:23:54.670 --> 00:23:56.160
I don't know if I've got enough
to feed you.


286
00:23:56.230 --> 00:23:57.720
Well, let's find out. 
How about that?

287
00:23:57.790 --> 00:23:58.837
Hey!

288
00:23:58.910 --> 00:24:01.038
Now, you got two of them
named James.


289
00:24:01.110 --> 00:24:02.271
Oh, you can call me Jim, Sister.

290
00:24:02.350 --> 00:24:03.476
And Orange is fine with me, ma'am.

291
00:24:03.550 --> 00:24:04.756
Or Big Fellow!

292
00:24:04.870 --> 00:24:06.759
All right. Well, this is fine with me.

293
00:24:06.910 --> 00:24:09.993
Mrs. Jackson. Hosea Williams.

294
00:24:10.070 --> 00:24:11.310
Or Castro!

295
00:24:11.390 --> 00:24:14.121
Oh, yeah, that's a long story.

296
00:24:14.190 --> 00:24:17.194
Those grits, they need some stirring.
Mind?


297
00:24:17.270 --> 00:24:18.795
You put your foot in it now.

298
00:24:19.230 --> 00:24:21.039
Ain't you supposed to be on a diet?

299
00:24:22.310 --> 00:24:23.471
Somebody call Juanita.

300
00:24:23.870 --> 00:24:26.840
- There's a phone!
- Hey, get off that phone.


301
00:24:26.910 --> 00:24:27.957
Juanita?

302
00:24:28.110 --> 00:24:30.351
<i>Don't do it, Doc. 
Don't do it...</i>

303
00:24:34.190 --> 00:24:36.158
Turning in, Doc. You okay?

304
00:24:36.990 --> 00:24:39.561
Yes, sir. Good night to you.

305
00:24:44.030 --> 00:24:47.273
I wanted to tell you that
the students are in town.


306
00:24:49.910 --> 00:24:51.196
Local students?

307
00:24:51.310 --> 00:24:53.074
Oh, no.

308
00:24:54.670 --> 00:24:57.071
The Student Non-Violent
Coordinating Committee.


309
00:24:58.190 --> 00:25:01.751
Okay. Our young friends at SNCC.

310
00:25:03.590 --> 00:25:04.671
Good to know.

311
00:25:04.750 --> 00:25:06.912
You the one told them to organize.

312
00:25:08.510 --> 00:25:09.511
Took it to heart.

313
00:25:10.230 --> 00:25:13.518
Don't be surprised
if they don't give us grief tomorrow.


314
00:25:13.590 --> 00:25:16.275
Town folk may be happy to see us.
But SNCC?


315
00:25:16.590 --> 00:25:19.116
They feel we're in their territory.

316
00:25:20.510 --> 00:25:23.320
They're young and full of spirit.

317
00:25:24.070 --> 00:25:25.401
Not a bad thing.

318
00:25:27.350 --> 00:25:29.159
It'll sort out.

319
00:25:31.870 --> 00:25:33.360
Good night.

320
00:25:35.590 --> 00:25:37.001
Good night.

321
00:25:40.710 --> 00:25:45.034
"Boycotting the buses in Montgomery.

322
00:25:45.110 --> 00:25:47.317
"Segregation in Birmingham."

323
00:25:48.710 --> 00:25:50.951
<i>Boycotting the buses in Montgomery.</i>

324
00:25:53.830 --> 00:25:56.640
<i>Segregation in Birmingham.</i>

325
00:25:58.230 --> 00:26:01.951
<i>Now? Voting in Selma.</i>

326
00:26:03.750 --> 00:26:08.119
<i>One struggle ends just to go
right to the next and the next.</i>


327
00:26:10.110 --> 00:26:13.114
<i>If you think of it that way,
it's a hard road.</i>


328
00:26:14.750 --> 00:26:17.401
<i>But I don't think of it that way.</i>

329
00:26:17.470 --> 00:26:20.235
<i>I think of these efforts as one effort.</i>

330
00:26:20.310 --> 00:26:23.120
<i>And that one effort is for our life.</i>

331
00:26:24.990 --> 00:26:29.598
<i>Our life as a community.
Our life as a nation.</i>


332
00:26:30.230 --> 00:26:32.153
<i>For our lives.</i>

333
00:26:37.510 --> 00:26:38.921
<i>We can do this.</i>

334
00:26:41.670 --> 00:26:43.195
<i>We must do this!</i>

335
00:26:45.510 --> 00:26:49.037
<i>We see children</i>

336
00:26:49.110 --> 00:26:51.875
<i>become victims of one
of the most vicious crimes</i>


337
00:26:51.950 --> 00:26:56.433
<i>ever perpetrated against humanity
within the walls of their own church!</i>


338
00:26:58.430 --> 00:27:01.400
<i>They are sainted now.</i>

339
00:27:01.470 --> 00:27:04.792
<i>They are the sainted ones
in this quest for freedom.</i>


340
00:27:04.870 --> 00:27:07.555
<i>And they speak to us still.</i>

341
00:27:07.630 --> 00:27:11.794
<i>They say to us, to all of us,
all colors and creeds,</i>


342
00:27:13.110 --> 00:27:14.760
<i>that we must do this.</i>

343
00:27:15.190 --> 00:27:20.196
<i>They say to us that it is unacceptable</i>

344
00:27:20.270 --> 00:27:23.638
<i>for more than 50%
of Selma to be Negro</i>

345
00:27:23.710 --> 00:27:27.237
<i>and yet less than 2% of Negroes here
being able to vote</i>


346
00:27:27.310 --> 00:27:30.314
<i>and determine their own destiny
as human beings.</i>


347
00:27:33.390 --> 00:27:37.520
<i>They say to us that
the local white leadership</i>


348
00:27:37.590 --> 00:27:40.992
<i>use their power to
keep us away from the ballot box</i>


349
00:27:41.070 --> 00:27:42.754
<i>and keep us voiceless.</i>

350
00:27:45.510 --> 00:27:50.198
<i>As long as I am unable to exercise
my constitutional right to vote,</i>


351
00:27:50.510 --> 00:27:53.241
<i>I do not have
command of my own life.</i>

352
00:27:53.310 --> 00:27:56.837
<i>I cannot determine my own destiny
for it is determined for me</i>


353
00:27:56.910 --> 00:28:00.153
<i>by people who would rather
see me suffer than succeed.</i>


354
00:28:00.910 --> 00:28:04.312
<i>Those that have gone before us say,
"No more!"</i>


355
00:28:04.390 --> 00:28:05.630
No more! No more!

356
00:28:05.710 --> 00:28:07.280
<i>No more!</i>

357
00:28:07.350 --> 00:28:11.150
<i>That means protest, that means march,</i>

358
00:28:11.230 --> 00:28:15.474
<i>that means disturb the peace,
that means jail,</i>


359
00:28:15.550 --> 00:28:17.951
<i>that means risk! 
And that is hard!</i>

360
00:28:20.430 --> 00:28:23.081
<i>We will not wait any longer.</i>

361
00:28:23.150 --> 00:28:25.152
<i>Give us the vote!</i>

362
00:28:25.230 --> 00:28:26.800
That's right! No more!

363
00:28:27.190 --> 00:28:29.352
<i>We're not asking. 
We're demanding.</i>

364
00:28:29.430 --> 00:28:30.636
<i>Give us the vote!</i>

365
00:28:30.710 --> 00:28:31.836
Give us the vote!

366
00:28:41.750 --> 00:28:45.471
Dr. King.
Roy Reed of <i>The New York Times.</i>


367
00:28:45.550 --> 00:28:47.552
Yes. Hello to you. How are you?

368
00:28:47.630 --> 00:28:49.951
I'm well, sir. 
Thank you for asking.

369
00:28:50.070 --> 00:28:54.917
Dr. King, are you truly non-violent
if you are provoking violence, sir?


370
00:28:54.990 --> 00:28:57.994
We are here,
using our very bodies in protest


371
00:28:58.070 --> 00:28:59.913
- to say to those who deny us...
- Dr. King. Dr. King.


372
00:28:59.990 --> 00:29:00.991
Pleasure, sir.

373
00:29:01.070 --> 00:29:03.835
...that we will no longer let them
use their billy clubs


374
00:29:03.910 --> 00:29:06.754
in dark corners and halls of power.

375
00:29:06.830 --> 00:29:09.595
We make them do it
in the glaring light of day, Mr. Reed.


376
00:29:09.670 --> 00:29:11.638
Is SNCC standing with us
on this or not, gentlemen?


377
00:29:11.710 --> 00:29:12.836
You want us to bring our people in,

378
00:29:12.910 --> 00:29:14.071
but you're not giving anything in return.

379
00:29:14.150 --> 00:29:16.596
Now we are asking
for some kind of commitment here.


380
00:29:16.670 --> 00:29:18.638
Respectfully speaking, of course,

381
00:29:18.710 --> 00:29:20.678
we've been handling
the voter registration


382
00:29:20.790 --> 00:29:22.554
in this town now for two years.

383
00:29:22.630 --> 00:29:24.997
Well, you haven't gotten very far,
have you?


384
00:29:26.270 --> 00:29:28.796
Well, maybe not, Reverend.
But we're still here.


385
00:29:28.870 --> 00:29:29.871
Meaning what?

386
00:29:29.950 --> 00:29:31.475
This time next month, you won't be!

387
00:29:31.550 --> 00:29:33.712
- That's insanity!
- Just like you left Albany.


388
00:29:33.790 --> 00:29:35.235
Those people are pathetic
down there now.


389
00:29:35.310 --> 00:29:36.471
Like they daddy left home!

390
00:29:36.550 --> 00:29:38.678
What we're trying
to explain is that in Albany you all...


391
00:29:38.750 --> 00:29:41.594
You know what I think?
Maybe we should just leave Selma...


392
00:29:41.670 --> 00:29:43.752
Now! Leave it to these two.

393
00:29:43.830 --> 00:29:46.071
Come back in another two years
and see how much further you got!


394
00:29:46.150 --> 00:29:47.959
- Sounds just fine to me.
- That's enough.


395
00:29:50.070 --> 00:29:51.071
Enough of this now.

396
00:29:54.030 --> 00:29:56.761
I haven't the time for this.
None of us got the time for this.


397
00:29:59.390 --> 00:30:00.915
John.

398
00:30:01.630 --> 00:30:02.961
James.

399
00:30:04.070 --> 00:30:07.711
The way our organization works
is straightforward.


400
00:30:07.790 --> 00:30:12.000
We negotiate. We demonstrate.
We resist.


401
00:30:12.470 --> 00:30:17.636
And on our best days, our adversary
helps the matter by making a mistake.


402
00:30:17.710 --> 00:30:22.193
Now, we were in Albany for nine months
and we made a lot of mistakes.


403
00:30:22.750 --> 00:30:25.356
But their sheriff, 
Laurie Pritchett,

404
00:30:25.750 --> 00:30:27.593
he never made a mistake.

405
00:30:27.710 --> 00:30:31.078
Kept his cool,
kept arresting us in a humane way,


406
00:30:31.150 --> 00:30:34.597
carried people to
the jail-wagons on stretchers.


407
00:30:34.670 --> 00:30:36.752
Day in, day out.

408
00:30:37.190 --> 00:30:38.157
There was no drama.

409
00:30:38.230 --> 00:30:39.755
You mean there was no cameras.

410
00:30:43.030 --> 00:30:44.031
Exactly.

411
00:30:45.470 --> 00:30:48.360
Now I know, we all understand,
that you young people


412
00:30:48.430 --> 00:30:51.240
believe in working
in the community long-term.


413
00:30:51.310 --> 00:30:55.156
Doing the good work
to raise black consciousness.


414
00:30:56.870 --> 00:30:58.952
It's good grassroots work.

415
00:30:59.030 --> 00:31:03.240
I can't tell you
how much we admire that.


416
00:31:04.390 --> 00:31:06.358
But what we do

417
00:31:06.430 --> 00:31:08.353
is negotiate,

418
00:31:08.430 --> 00:31:10.000
demonstrate,

419
00:31:10.070 --> 00:31:11.151
resist.

420
00:31:11.270 --> 00:31:13.318
And a big part of that

421
00:31:13.390 --> 00:31:16.519
is raising white consciousness.

422
00:31:16.590 --> 00:31:17.921
And in particular the consciousness

423
00:31:17.990 --> 00:31:19.754
of whichever white man
happens to be sitting


424
00:31:19.830 --> 00:31:20.831
in the Oval Office.

425
00:31:21.550 --> 00:31:26.033
Right now, Johnson has other fish to fry
and he'll ignore us if he can.


426
00:31:27.150 --> 00:31:29.801
The only way to stop him doing that

427
00:31:29.870 --> 00:31:32.601
is by being on the front page
of the national press every morning


428
00:31:33.270 --> 00:31:37.036
and by being on the TV news
every night.


429
00:31:37.110 --> 00:31:39.158
And that requires

430
00:31:39.990 --> 00:31:41.151
drama.

431
00:31:42.630 --> 00:31:43.791
Now...

432
00:31:46.350 --> 00:31:47.556
John.

433
00:31:49.750 --> 00:31:51.115
James.

434
00:31:51.190 --> 00:31:52.919
Answer me one question.

435
00:31:54.190 --> 00:31:58.912
I've been told the sheriff in this town
isn't like Laurie Pritchett in Albany.


436
00:31:58.990 --> 00:32:03.279
He's a big ignorant bully
like Bull Connor in Birmingham.


437
00:32:04.510 --> 00:32:07.434
Well, you tell me. 
You know Selma.

438
00:32:07.510 --> 00:32:09.956
You know Sheriff Jim Clark.

439
00:32:10.870 --> 00:32:15.558
Is he Laurie Pritchett?
Or is he Bull Connor?


440
00:32:25.270 --> 00:32:26.271
He's Bull Connor.

441
00:32:27.030 --> 00:32:28.873
- Bingo!
- Good.


442
00:32:31.190 --> 00:32:32.521
That's good.

443
00:32:35.670 --> 00:32:36.751
But it gets better.

444
00:32:37.350 --> 00:32:41.275
<i>See, Clark doesn't control the streets
like Connor did in Birmingham.</i>


445
00:32:41.350 --> 00:32:42.590
<i>Clark's the County Sheriff,</i>

446
00:32:42.670 --> 00:32:45.799
<i>and all he controls in Selma
is the County Courthouse.</i>


447
00:32:45.870 --> 00:32:47.281
<i>So relatively speaking,</i>

448
00:32:47.390 --> 00:32:52.157
<i>we have clear avenues of approach
to a defined battle zone.</i>


449
00:33:46.950 --> 00:33:50.193
<i>In the courthouse
sits the heart of the matter,</i>


450
00:33:50.270 --> 00:33:52.591
<i>the voter registration office.</i>

451
00:33:52.670 --> 00:33:54.513
<i>Now this is
an exceptional circumstance.</i>


452
00:33:54.590 --> 00:33:58.675
<i>See, in Albany, there were
no clearly defined battle zones.</i>


453
00:33:58.750 --> 00:34:03.039
<i>The issue was segregation,
and segregation was everywhere.</i>


454
00:34:03.110 --> 00:34:08.116
<i>In Selma, we can concentrate
our actions on one building.</i>


455
00:34:08.590 --> 00:34:10.957
<i>A citadel, defended by fanatics.</i>

456
00:34:11.950 --> 00:34:13.475
<i>The Selma Courthouse.</i>

457
00:34:14.630 --> 00:34:16.394
<i>A perfect stage.</i>

458
00:34:31.910 --> 00:34:34.311
Y'all deliberately
causing an obstruction!


459
00:34:35.630 --> 00:34:37.871
You don't disperse,
you're gonna be arrested.


460
00:34:37.950 --> 00:34:39.076
I promise you!

461
00:34:39.150 --> 00:34:40.834
Sheriff Clark,

462
00:34:40.910 --> 00:34:43.754
we're trying to gain access
to the registration office.


463
00:34:43.830 --> 00:34:45.400
Which is our legal right.

464
00:34:45.510 --> 00:34:48.081
There's too many of you.
And you know damn well there is!


465
00:34:48.150 --> 00:34:50.312
Now, y'all just gonna have
to wait at the rear!


466
00:34:50.430 --> 00:34:51.955
No, Sheriff Clark.

467
00:34:52.030 --> 00:34:55.512
We're going in the front
and we're gonna wait right here.


468
00:34:55.590 --> 00:34:58.912
Segregation is now illegal
in this country, sir.


469
00:35:01.470 --> 00:35:02.551
Get out, nigger.

470
00:35:02.630 --> 00:35:03.677
- Come on.
- I'm trying.


471
00:35:03.750 --> 00:35:04.831
Kneel down, Daddy.

472
00:35:05.830 --> 00:35:07.116
Come on.

473
00:35:07.470 --> 00:35:09.313
Keep this sidewalk clear. Clear a path!

474
00:35:09.670 --> 00:35:12.150
Get out of the way! 
Get out of the way!

475
00:35:12.230 --> 00:35:13.641
Get the hell out of the way!

476
00:35:13.710 --> 00:35:15.519
Keep the sidewalk clear!

477
00:35:15.870 --> 00:35:17.076
I said keep it clear!

478
00:35:17.150 --> 00:35:18.640
Okay. We about to sit him down.
He can't sit.


479
00:35:18.750 --> 00:35:19.831
Then he needs to learn.

480
00:35:19.910 --> 00:35:21.639
- He gonna sit.
- Sit down, God damn it!


481
00:35:21.710 --> 00:35:23.474
Hey, hey! Pa? Pa?

482
00:35:23.870 --> 00:35:25.281
Daddy.

483
00:35:26.910 --> 00:35:28.594
I just told you he can't sit.

484
00:35:28.670 --> 00:35:30.035
What do we got here?

485
00:35:31.110 --> 00:35:32.111
What's going on here, boy?

486
00:35:32.190 --> 00:35:33.476
What we got here? 
What we got here?

487
00:35:33.550 --> 00:35:35.393
- Jimmie! Sit down!
- No, Mama, I'm sick of this.


488
00:35:35.470 --> 00:35:36.596
- Jimmie!
- Don't do it.


489
00:35:36.670 --> 00:35:37.637
Do you have a problem, boy?

490
00:35:37.710 --> 00:35:39.360
I'm sick of this! 
I just told you...

491
00:35:39.430 --> 00:35:41.831
What'd you think, boy?
What'd you think?


492
00:35:41.910 --> 00:35:43.560
What the fuck are you thinking?

493
00:35:54.230 --> 00:35:55.516
Get that nigger woman!

494
00:35:55.590 --> 00:35:56.796
Kill that nigger bitch!

495
00:35:57.470 --> 00:35:58.676
Get your hands off of me!

496
00:36:14.550 --> 00:36:17.952
